{"title_page": "William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley", "text_new": "{{short description|British landowner and benefactor}}\n{{other people|William Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name        = The Early of Dudley\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image       = Earl of Dudley Vanity Fair 18 June 1870.JPG\n| caption     = ''The Earl of Dudley as caricatured by Ape ([[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Carlo Pellegrini]]) in'' [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], ''June 1870''\n| birth_name  = William Ward\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1817|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Edwardstone]], [[Boxford, Suffolk]]\n| death_date  = {{dda|1885|05|07|1817|03|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place =\n| education   = [[Eton College]] \n| alma_mater  = [[Christ Church, Oxford]]<br>[[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n| parents     = [[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Ward, 10th Baron Ward]]<br>Amelia Pillans\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Selina Constance de Burgh<br>|24 April 1851|14 November 1851|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|[[Georgina Ward, Countess of Dudley|Georgina Elisabeth Moncreiffe]]<br>|21 November 1865|7 May 1885|reason=his death}}\n| children    = 7\n}}\n\n'''William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley''' (27 March 1817 \u2013 7 May 1885), known as '''The Lord Ward''' from 1835 to 1860, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] landowner and benefactor.\n\n==Background and education==\nWard was born on 27 March 1817 at [[Edwardstone]], Boxford, Suffolk, England, the son of [[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Ward, 10th Baron Ward]], who had succeeded in the barony of Ward on the death of his second cousin, Foreign Secretary [[John Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]], in 1833 (the earldom becoming extinct). His mother was Amelia, daughter of William Cooch Pillans.\n\nHe was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://www.thepeerage.com/p281.htm#i2803 thepeerage.com William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]</ref> He played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Oxford University Cricket Club]] between 1838 and 1842.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37882/37882.html Cricket Archive: Lord Ward]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Memorial to William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley.jpg|thumb|300px|The monument to William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley, in [[Worcester Cathedral]]]]\nOn 6 December 1835, he inherited the title of Lord Ward, when he became the 11th Baron Ward.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KCZBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA367|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire|last=Burke|first=Sir Bernard|date=1869|publisher=Harrison and Sons|isbn=|location=London|pages=367-368|language=en}}</ref> His inheritance included [[Himley Hall]] and the ruins of [[Dudley Castle]]. In 1837 his trustees purchased the [[Witley Court]] estate in Worcestershire from [[Thomas Foley, 4th Baron Foley]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nWard never held any political office,<ref name=\"Complete peerage\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka|title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant|last=Cokayne|first=George Edward|date=1910|publisher=The St. Catherine Press, Ltd.|others=|isbn=|volume=4|location=London|pages=490}}</ref> but served as Colonel Commander of the [[Queen's Own Worcestershire Hussars|Worcestershire Yeomanry]] in 1854.<ref name=\"Complete peerage\"/>\n\nBetween 1859 and 1877 Ward paid for the entire refacing and restoration of [[Worcester Cathedral]]<ref name=\"Folkes, J. Homery p9\">Folkes, J. Homery ''The Victorian Architect and [[George Edmund Street]]'' Transactions of the Worcestershire Archaeological Society. Third Series Vol 4 1974 p9</ref> and there is a monument to him in the cathedral. In 1868 he defrayed one third of the cost of the tower and spire of St John the Baptist's Church at [[Hagley]].<ref name=\"Folkes, J. Homery p9\"/> He was also a trustee of the [[National Gallery]] and the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\nIn 1860, the earldom held by his kinsman was revived when he was created '''Viscount Ednam''', of [[Ednam]] in the County of Roxburgh, and '''Earl of Dudley''', of [[Dudley Castle]] in the County of Stafford.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=22356 |date=14 February 1860 |page=518 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Dudley married, firstly, Selina Constance, daughter of Hubert de Burgh, on 24 April 1851. She died on 14 November of the same year, aged only 22. There were no children from this marriage.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\">{{cite web |title=Dudley, Earl of (UK, 1860) |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/dudley1860.htm |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe married, secondly, [[Georgina Ward, Countess of Dudley|Georgina Elisabeth]], daughter of [[Sir Thomas Moncreiffe, 7th Baronet]], and Lady Louisa Hay-Drummond, on 21 November 1865. His sister-in-law [[Harriet Mordaunt|Harriet Moncreiffe]], who a few years later, as Lady Mordaunt, became embroiled in a sensational divorce case, referred to him as \"frizzle wig\".<ref>Hamilton, Elizabeth (1999) ''The Warwickshire Scandal''</ref>  Together, William and Georgina were the parents of six sons and one daughter:<ref name=\"Peerage\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p281.htm#i2803 | title=William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley | publisher=www.thepeerage.com | date=26 December 2012 | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> \n\n* [[William Humble Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley]] (1867\u20131932), who succeeded his father and became a prominent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who married Rachel Gurney CBE, the youngest daughter of Charles Henry Gurney.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* [[John Hubert Ward|Hon. Sir John Hubert Ward]] (1870\u20131938), who married [[Jean Templeton Reid]], daughter of U.S. Ambassador [[Whitelaw Reid]].<ref name=\"1908Wedding\">{{cite news|title=MISS REID MARRIED AT ST. JAMES'S; To Mr. Ward, the Bridegroom, the King Says, \"Well Done, Johnny.\" QUEEN KISSES THE BRIDE Brilliant Assemblage in the Chapel Royal and at Dorchester House Afterward.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/06/24/archives/miss-reid-married-at-st-jamess-to-mr-ward-the-bridegroom-the-king.html|accessdate=15 November 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 June 1908}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Ward (British politician)|Hon. Robert Arthur Ward]] (1871\u20131942), who married Lady Mary Acheson, a daughter of [[Archibald Acheson, 4th Earl of Gosford]] and Lady Louisa Montagu (daughter of [[William Montagu, 7th Duke of Manchester]]).<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Lady Edith Amelia Ward (1872\u20131956), who married [[Frederick Glyn, 4th Baron Wolverton]].<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Captain Hon. Reginald Ward, [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] (1874\u20131904), of the [[Royal Horse Guards]].<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Captain Hon. Cyril Augustus Ward (1876\u20131930), who married Baroness Irene de Brienen, a daughter of Baron de Brienen.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Hon. Gerald Ernest Francis Ward {{post-nominals|Royal Victorian Order|MVO}}<ref name=\"CGWC\"/> (1877\u20131914), a first-class cricketer for [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC),<ref name=\"Cricket \">{{cite web | url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/33/33619/33619.html | title=Gerald Ward | publisher=Cricket Archive | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> who served in the [[Life Guards (United Kingdom)|1st Life Guards]]  during the [[First World War]] and was killed in action<ref name=\"CGWC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/912919| title=Ward, the Hon. Gerald Ernest Francis | publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> at [[Zandvoorde (Zonnebeke)|Zandvoorde]], Belgium. He married Lady Evelyn Crichton, a daughter of [[John Crichton, 4th Earl Erne]] and Lady Florence Cole (daughter of [[William Cole, 3rd Earl of Enniskillen]]).<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n\nWard died on 7 May 1885, aged 68, at Dudley House, [[Park Lane (road)|Park Lane]], [[Mayfair]], in [[London]], and was buried in [[Great Witley]], [[Worcestershire]]. His remains were later reinterred in [[Worcester Cathedral]].  The Countess of Dudley survived her husband by over forty years and died in February 1929 at her home at [[Pembroke Lodge, Richmond Park]]<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news | title=Death of Georgina, Lady Dudley: A Great Lady of the Victorian Age | work=[[Glasgow Herald]] | date=9 February 1929 }}</ref> at the age of 82, having spent over half her life as a widow.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-william-ward-5 | William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley }}\n*{{Find a Grave|5397}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Earl of Dudley]]\n | years  = 1860\u20131885 \n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|William Humble Ward]] }}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Humble Ward]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Baron Ward]]\n | years  = 1835\u20131885 \n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|William Humble Ward]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, William Ward, 1st Earl of}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Burials at Worcester Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of 1826 to 1863]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Oxford University cricketers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Marylebone Cricket Club]]\n[[Category:Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Ward family|William]]\n[[Category:Edwardstone]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British landowner and benefactor}}\n{{other people|William Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name        = The Early of Dudley\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image       = Earl of Dudley Vanity Fair 18 June 1870.JPG\n| caption     = ''The Earl of Dudley as caricatured by Ape ([[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Carlo Pellegrini]]) in'' [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], ''June 1870''\n| birth_name  = William Ward\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1817|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Edwardstone]], [[Boxford, Suffolk]]\n| death_date  = {{dda|1885|05|07|1817|03|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place =\n| education   = [[Eton College]] \n| alma_mater  = [[Christ Church, Oxford]]<br>[[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n| parents     = [[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Ward, 10th Baron Ward]]<br>Amelia Pillans\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Selina Constance de Burgh<br>|24 April 1851|14 November 1851|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|[[Georgina Ward, Countess of Dudley|Georgina Elisabeth Moncreiffe]]<br>|21 November 1865|7 May 1885|reason=his death}}\n| children    = 7\n}}\n\n'''William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley''' (27 March 1817 \u2013 7 May 1885), known as '''The Lord Ward''' from 1835 to 1860, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] landowner and benefactor.\n\n==Background and education==\nWard was born on 27 March 1817 at [[Edwardstone]], Boxford, Suffolk, England, the son of [[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Ward, 10th Baron Ward]], who had succeeded in the barony of Ward on the death of his second cousin, Foreign Secretary [[John Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]], in 1833 (the earldom becoming extinct). His mother was Amelia, daughter of William Cooch Pillans.\n\nHe was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://www.thepeerage.com/p281.htm#i2803 thepeerage.com William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]</ref> He played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Oxford University Cricket Club]] between 1838 and 1842.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37882/37882.html Cricket Archive: Lord Ward]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Memorial to William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley.jpg|thumb|300px|The monument to William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley, in [[Worcester Cathedral]]]]\nOn 6 December 1835, he inherited the title of Lord Ward, when he became the 11th Baron Ward.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KCZBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA367|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire|last=Burke|first=Sir Bernard|date=1869|publisher=Harrison and Sons|isbn=|location=London|pages=367-368|language=en}}</ref> His inheritance included [[Himley Hall]] and the ruins of [[Dudley Castle]]. In 1837 his trustees purchased the [[Witley Court]] estate in Worcestershire from [[Thomas Foley, 4th Baron Foley]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nWard never held any political office,<ref name=\"Complete peerage\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka|title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant|last=Cokayne|first=George Edward|date=1910|publisher=The St. Catherine Press, Ltd.|others=|isbn=|volume=4|location=London|pages=490}}</ref> but served as Colonel Commander of the [[Queen's Own Worcestershire Hussars|Worcestershire Yeomanry]] in 1854.<ref name=\"Complete peerage\"/>\n\nBetween 1859 and 1877 Ward paid for the entire refacing and restoration of [[Worcester Cathedral]]<ref name=\"Folkes, J. Homery p9\">Folkes, J. Homery ''The Victorian Architect and [[George Edmund Street]]'' Transactions of the Worcestershire Archaeological Society. Third Series Vol 4 1974 p9</ref> and there is a monument to him in the cathedral. In 1868 he defrayed one third of the cost of the tower and spire of St John the Baptist's Church at [[Hagley]].<ref name=\"Folkes, J. Homery p9\"/> He was also a trustee of the [[National Gallery]] and the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\nIn 1860, the earldom held by his kinsman was revived when he was created '''Viscount Ednam''', of [[Ednam]] in the County of Roxburgh, and '''Earl of Dudley''', of [[Dudley Castle]] in the County of Stafford.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=22356 |date=14 February 1860 |page=518 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Dudley married, firstly, Selina Constance, daughter of Hubert de Burgh, on 24 April 1851. She died on 14 November of the same year, aged only 22. There were no children from this marriage.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\">{{cite web |title=Dudley, Earl of (UK, 1860) |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/dudley1860.htm |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe married, secondly, [[Georgina Ward, Countess of Dudley|Georgina Elisabeth]], daughter of [[Sir Thomas Moncreiffe, 7th Baronet]], and Lady Louisa Hay-Drummond, on 21 November 1865. His sister-in-law [[Harriet Mordaunt|Harriet Moncreiffe]], who a few years later, as Lady Mordaunt, became embroiled in a sensational divorce case, referred to him as \"frizzle wig\".<ref>Hamilton, Elizabeth (1999) ''The Warwickshire Scandal''</ref>  Together, William and Georgina were the parents of six sons and one daughter:<ref name=\"Peerage\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p281.htm#i2803 | title=William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley | publisher=www.thepeerage.com | date=26 December 2012 | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> \n\n* [[William Humble Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley]] (1867\u20131932), who succeeded his father and became a prominent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who married Rachel Gurney CBE, the youngest daughter of Charles Henry Gurney.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* [[John Hubert Ward|Hon. Sir John Hubert Ward]] (1870\u20131938), who married [[Jean Templeton Reid]], daughter of U.S. Ambassador [[Whitelaw Reid]].<ref name=\"1908Wedding\">{{cite news|title=MISS REID MARRIED AT ST. JAMES'S; To Mr. Ward, the Bridegroom, the King Says, \"Well Done, Johnny.\" QUEEN KISSES THE BRIDE Brilliant Assemblage in the Chapel Royal and at Dorchester House Afterward.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/06/24/archives/miss-reid-married-at-st-jamess-to-mr-ward-the-bridegroom-the-king.html|accessdate=15 November 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 June 1908}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Ward (British politician)|Hon. Robert Arthur Ward]] (1871\u20131942), who married Lady Mary Acheson, a daughter of [[Archibald Acheson, 4th Earl of Gosford]] and Lady Louisa Montagu (daughter of [[William Montagu, 7th Duke of Manchester]]).<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Lady Edith Amelia Ward (1872\u20131956), who married [[Frederick Glyn, 4th Baron Wolverton]].<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Captain Hon. Reginald Ward, [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] (1874\u20131904), of the [[Royal Horse Guards]].<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Captain Hon. Cyril Augustus Ward (1876\u20131930), who married Baroness Irene de Brienen, a daughter of Baron de Brienen.<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n* Hon. Gerald Ernest Francis Ward {{post-nominals|Royal Victorian Order|MVO}}<ref name=\"CGWC\"/> (1877\u20131914), a first-class cricketer for [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC),<ref name=\"Cricket \">{{cite web | url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/33/33619/33619.html | title=Gerald Ward | publisher=Cricket Archive | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> who served in the [[Life Guards (United Kingdom)|1st Life Guards]]  during the [[First World War]] and was killed in action<ref name=\"CGWC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/912919| title=Ward, the Hon. Gerald Ernest Francis | publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] | accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> at [[Zandvoorde (Zonnebeke)|Zandvoorde]], Belgium. He married Lady Evelyn Crichton, a daughter of [[John Crichton, 4th Earl Erne]] and Lady Florence Cole (daughter of [[William Cole, 3rd Earl of Enniskillen]]).<ref name=\"EarlDudley\"/>\n\nWard died on 7 May 1885, aged 68, at Dudley House, [[Park Lane (road)|Park Lane]], [[Mayfair]], in [[London]], and was buried in [[Great Witley]], [[Worcestershire]]. His remains were later reinterred in [[Worcester Cathedral]].  The Countess of Dudley survived her husband by over forty years and died in February 1929 at her home at [[Pembroke Lodge, Richmond Park]]<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news | title=Death of Georgina, Lady Dudley: A Great Lady of the Victorian Age | work=[[Glasgow Herald]] | date=9 February 1929 }}</ref> at the age of 82, having spent over half her life as a widow.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-william-ward-5 | William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley }}\n*{{Find a Grave|5397}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Earl of Dudley]]\n | years  = 1860\u20131885 \n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|William Humble Ward]] }}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[William Humble Ward, 10th Baron Ward|William Humble Ward]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Baron Ward]]\n | years  = 1835\u20131885 \n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|William Humble Ward]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, William Ward, 1st Earl of}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Burials at Worcester Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of 1826 to 1863]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Oxford University cricketers]]\n[[Category:People educat